// =============================================================================
// Modulus library — EXPENSIVE. Do not use these unless you specifically need
// to.
// =============================================================================
//
// Every function in this file is derived from the modulus operation and is
// significantly more expensive than the operations in `math.su`. They exist
// for JavaScript / TypeScript / C# / Rust compatibility. Most JS programs
// reach for `Math.floor`, `Math.ceil`, `%` etc. as if they were free — on
// Sutra's substrate they are not, because the substrate is fundamentally a
// vector-space machine and "round this scalar down to the nearest integer"
// is an operation that requires either a transcendental decomposition
// (Fourier sawtooth) or a hardware rounding instruction applied to a tensor.
//
// The fact that this is a separate library — not a section of `math.su` —
// is intentional. If you find yourself importing it heavily, your program
// is probably leaning on a non-vector-shaped algorithm and a rewrite that
// stays in the linear/tensor regime will outperform.
//
// All declarations here extend `class Math` so the JS-shaped call sites
// (`Math.floor(x)`, `Math.abs(x)`, `Math.sign(x)`) compile without
// special-case routing — the stdlib loader picks up static methods from
// every Math-class declaration across the stdlib and merges them into one
// namespace.
//
// The `%` operator dispatches directly to `Math.fmod` (truncation modulus,
// JS / C / Rust / C# / TS semantics — result has the sign of the
// dividend). `Math.mod` is the floor-modulus variant (always non-negative
// for positive divisor) and is the eigen-rotation-built substrate-pure
// form that's preserved here as the differentiable building block. Use it
// directly when you want JS-incompatible mathematical floor-mod.

class Math extends vector {
    // Truncation modulus (JS / C / C# / Rust / TS `%`). Result has the
    // sign of x. `fmod(-1, 3) == -1`, `fmod(-0.1, 1) == -0.1`. This is
    // what the `%` operator lowers to.
    static intrinsic method scalar fmod(scalar x, scalar m);

    // Floor / mathematical modulus. Result is always non-negative when
    // m > 0. `mod(-1, 3) == 2`, `mod(-0.1, 1) == 0.9`. Aliases the
    // current best-performing implementation — today that's
    // rotation_mod; benchmark in experiments/modulus_comparison.py
    // compares the two side by side.
    static intrinsic method scalar mod(scalar x, scalar m);

    // Floor mod via eigen rotation: exact away from boundaries,
    // discontinuous at integer multiples of m. Cheaper per call
    // (2 trig lookups + atan2) than sawtooth_mod, less smooth.
    static intrinsic method scalar rotation_mod(scalar x, scalar m);

    // Floor mod via Fourier series of the sawtooth: smooth and
    // differentiable everywhere, with ~9% Gibbs overshoot near
    // boundaries. Built from N sin lookups (N = 16 default).
    static intrinsic method scalar sawtooth_mod(scalar x, scalar m);

    // Round toward negative infinity. `floor(3.7) == 3`,
    // `floor(-0.1) == -1`.
    static intrinsic method scalar floor(scalar x);

    // Round toward positive infinity. `ceil(3.2) == 4`,
    // `ceil(-0.1) == 0`.
    static intrinsic method scalar ceil(scalar x);

    // Round to nearest integer, ties to even (banker's rounding) per
    // the substrate's default. JS `Math.round` uses half-up — see the
    // queue's substrate-purity audit item for the discrepancy.
    static intrinsic method scalar round(scalar x);

    // Truncate toward zero. `trunc(3.7) == 3`, `trunc(-3.7) == -3`.
    static intrinsic method scalar trunc(scalar x);

    // Absolute value.
    static intrinsic method scalar abs(scalar x);

    // Sign of x. Returns -1, 0, or +1.
    static intrinsic method scalar sign(scalar x);
}
